definition.value: A 1-acyl-2-hexadecanoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphate in which the 1-acyl group is specified as oleoyl (9Z-octadecaenoyl).
A 1-acyl-2-octadecanoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphate in which the 1-acyl group is specified as oleoyl (9Z-octadecaenoyl).
A 1-acyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the 1-acyl substituent is specified as heptadecanoyl.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as heptadecanoyl and oleoyl respectively.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as oleoyl and heptadecanoyl respectively.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as stearoyl and oleoyl respectively.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as oleoyl and linoleoyl respectively.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the 1-acyl substituent is specified as stearoyl (octadecanoyl).
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as oleoyl and pentadecanoyl respectively.

An inorganic chloride salt with formula SbCl3. It is used as a reagent for detecting vitamin A and related carotenoids, reacting with the carotenoid to form a blue complex that can be measured by colorimetry (the Carr-Price test). Solutions of antimony trichloride were formerly used for dissolving and removing horn stubs from calves and goats.
A methyl glycoside that is beta-D-xylose in which the hydrogen of the anomeric hydroxy group is replaced by a methyl group.
An aldopentose derivative that is formally obtained from a xylose.

A radium molecular entity with formula (223)RaCl2. Used as as a radiotherapeutic agent for the treatment of patients with castration-resistant prostate cancer, symptomatic bone metastases and no known visceral metastatic disease. An alpha-emitter, radium-223 has a half-life of 11.4 days.
A methyl-branched fatty acid that is pentanoic acid with a methyl group substituent at position 4. It is a metabolite of 20 alpha-hydroxycholesterol
A  branched-chain saturated fatty acid anion that is pentanoate with a methyl group substituent at position 4.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as oleoyl and tetradecanoyl respectively.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the 1-acyl substituent is specified as gamma-linolenoyl (6Z,9Z,12Z-octadecatrienoyl).
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as gamma-linolenoyl and oleoyl respectively.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the 1-acyl substituent is specified as arachidoyl (icosanoyl).
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as arachidoyl and oleoyl respectively.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as myristoyl and oleoyl respectively.
Any oligosaccharide that has a biosynthetic pathway in common with that of raffinose.
A phosphatidylcholine 38:6 in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 are specified as hexadecanoyl and (4Z,7Z,10Z,13Z,16Z,19Z)-docosahexaenoyl respectively.
A phosphatidylcholine 38:4 in which the two acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as stearoyl and arachidonoyl respectively.
A 1-O-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl group is specified as lauroyl (dodecanoyl)
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the two acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as lauroyl and arachidonoyl respectively.
A 1-O-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl group is specified as icosanoyl.
A phosphatidylcholine 40:4 in which the two acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as icosanoyl and arachidonoyl respectively.
A glycosylglucose in which the glycosyl moiety is L-rhamnose linked alpha to C-3 of beta-D-glucose.
A phosphatidylcholine 28:0 in which the two acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as lauroyl and palmitoyl respectively.
A phosphatidylcholine 28:0 in which the two acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as palmitoyl and lauroyl respectively.
A phosphatidylcholine 34:0 in which the two acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as stearoyl and palmitoyl respectively.
A phosphatidylcholine 36:1 in which the phosphatidyl acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are stearoyl and oleoyl respectively.

A glycopeptide originally isolated from the bacterium Streptomyces verticillus which contains a (4'R)-4',5'-dihydro-2,4'-bi-1,3-thiazole-2',4-diyl moiety with a a 4-guanidylbutylaminocarbonyl group attached to the 4-position of the terminal thiazole ring. Like all phleomycins, phleomycin D1 can form complexes with redox-active metals such as Co, Cu, and Fe.

Colourless, endogenous or exogenous pigment precursors that may be transformed by biological mechanisms into coloured compounds. They are used in biochemical assays and in diagnosis as indicators, particularly in the form of enzyme substrates.

An indolyl carbohydrate that is the beta-D-galactoside of 3-hydroxy-1H-indole in which the indole moiety is substituted at positions 4 and 5 by chlorine and bromine, respectively. It is used to test for the presence of an enzyme, beta-galactosidase, which cleaved the glycosidic bond to give 5-bromo-4-chloro-3-hydroxy-1H-indole, which immediately dimerises to give an intensely blue product.
A phosphatidylcholine 30:0 in which the phosphatidyl acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are myristoyl (tetradecanoyl) and palmitoyl (hexadecanoyl) respectively.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero 3-phosphocholine in which the acyl group at position 1 is unspecified while that at position 2 is specified as arachidonoyl
A broad-spectrum highly toxic antibiotic or mixture of antibiotics produced by a streptomyces (Streptomyces fradiae) and used medically especially to treat local infections.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the 1-acyl substituent is specified as palmitoleoyl.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are both (9Z)-hexadecenoyl (palmitoleoyl).
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as octadecanoyl and (9Z)-hexadecenoyl respectively.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as (9Z)-octadecenoyl and (9Z)-hexadecenoyl respectively.
A C13 straight-chain saturated fatty acid where the aliphatic hydrogens have been replaced by deuterium atoms.
Any C15 straight-chain monounsaturated fatty acid having one C=C double bond.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the acyl group at position 1 is unspecified while that at position 2 is specified as oleoyl
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the acyl group at position 1 is unspecified while that at position 2 is specified as linoleoyl
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the acyl group at position 1 is unspecified while that at position 2 is specified as arachidonoyl
A 1-acyl-2-arachidonoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphate(2-) in which the 1-acyl substituent is specified as oleoyl.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as oleoyl and arachidoyl respectively.
